==Old English==
===Etymology===
West Germanic *''[[gelwa]]'', from Indo-European ''*ghel-, *ghelə-'' ‘shine, glisten’.  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon ''gelo'' (Dutch ''[[geel]]''), Old High German ''[[gelo]]'' (German ''[[gelb]]''), Old Norse ''[[gulr]]'' (Swedish ''[[gul]]'').  The Indo-European root is also the source of Greek [[χλωρος|χλωρός]] ‘pale green’, Latin ''[[helvus]]'' ‘honey-yellow’, Old Irish ''gel'' ‘bright white’, Lithuanian ''[[želvas]]'' ‘greenish, golden’, Old Church Slavonic [[зеленъ]] (Russian [[зелёный]] ‘green’, compare ''[[zelen]]'')
===Adjective===
'''ġeolu''' (pl. ''ġeolwe'')

# [[yellow]]
#:''Him beoþ ða eagan geolwe.'' His eyes will be yellow.

